whereas.text:
Whereas the Convention both recognizes and provides the
			 basis for international cooperation in the control of international trade to
			 not threaten species’ survival;

Whereas high levels of exploitation of and trade in wild
			 animals and plants, together with other factors such as habitat loss, are
			 capable of bringing some species close to extinction;

Whereas parties to the Convention have an international
			 obligation and responsibility to protect endangered animals and plants
			 worldwide;

Whereas it is widely accepted that adherence to protective
			 measures adopted by the parties to the Convention has benefitted the
			 conservation of animals and plants;

Whereas nearly 5,000 species of animals and 29,000 species
			 of plants are protected by the Convention against over-exploitation through
			 international trade;

Whereas a proposal to move the polar bear from appendix II
			 to appendix I was rejected at the 16th meeting of the Conference of the
			 Parties;

paragraph.text:
applauds the
			 Convention’s recent leadership in reaffirming strong protections for the
			 African elephant, five sharks, and other endangered species;
